olicy paper on ‘Safeguarding the position of EU citizens in the UK and UK nationals in the EU’, which is availableat the following link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/safeguarding-the-position-of-eu-citizens-in-the-uk-and-uk-nationals-in-the-eu" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/safeguarding-the-position-of-eu-citizens-in-the-uk-and-uk-nationals-in-the-eu</a></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","1102 ; 1103","2017-06-30T08:13:45.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732494/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732494/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732494/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-06-26","Immigration: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps she is taking to ensure EU citizens who have not acquired five years residency and arrived before the cut-off date are able to prove their UK residency when travelling between the UK and the EU after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart Malcolm McDonald","1104"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732495","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-07-04","<p>The National Shipbuilding Strategy is a matter for the UK Government. We have consulted widely with Industry and the Trades Unions across the UK, including in Scotland. We will engage with the Scottish Government in due course.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-07-04T14:17:46.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732495/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732495/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732495/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-06-26","Warships: Shipbuilding","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what recent discussions he has had with the Scottish Government on the publication and implementation of the national shipbuilding strategy.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart Malcolm McDonald","1075"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732496","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-06-29","<p>There are no plans to reconsider the Ministry of Defence's intent to close eight military bases in Scotland. Consolidating the estate in Scotland enables us to release sites which do not effectively accommodate the military capabilities based there, and invest in significantly improved facilities to better support the men and women of our Armed Forces.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-06-29T15:12:11.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732496/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732496/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732496/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-06-26","Military Bases: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will make it his Department's policy to reconsider the closure of eight military bases in Scotland.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart Malcolm McDonald","1076"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732497","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-04","<p>The Government expects social media companies, and internet platforms, to have robust processes in place and to act promptly when all forms of abuse, including cyber bullying is reported. That includes acting quickly to removing inappropriate content, and where appropriate, suspending or terminating the accounts of those breaching the rules in place. We are continuing to work closely with industry, including social media companies, charities, schools and parents to tackle this serious issue.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-07-04T10:30:03.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732497/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732497/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732497/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-06-26","Social Media: Bullying","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps she is taking to ensure social media companies tackle cyber bullying.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart Malcolm McDonald","1077"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732498","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-04","<p>Network Rail is delivering the Great Western Electrification Programme to the dates set out in the latest publication of their Enhancement Delivery plan. This includes completing electrification of the Great Western Mainline between London and Bristol Parkway and on to Cardiff by December 2018.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-07-04T15:27:05.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732498/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732498/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732498/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-06-26","Great Western Railway Line: Electrification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he expects to announce whether the Great Western mainline to Bristol will be fully electrified; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Karin Smyth","Bristol South","Karin Smyth","1172"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732499","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-04","<p>Frequency and journey times on the Great Western mainline will be decided as part of the industry timetabling process which will in turn inform the improved capacity of the network.</p><p> </p><p>Once the current programme is complete, over 100 million rail journey experiences will improve each year, there will be an extra 4,900 extra seats into London and it is expected that journey times between London, Bristol, Cardiff and Swansea will reduce by around 15 minutes.</p><p> </p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-07-04T15:30:10.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732499/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732499/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732499/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-06-26","Great Western Railway Line: Electrification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the benefits for passengers in terms of capacity, frequency and journey times of the full electrification of the Great Western mainline to Bristol.","false","Biography information for Karin Smyth","Bristol South","Karin Smyth","1173"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732500","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-04","<p>The Office of Rail and Road is the independent economic and safety regulator for the railways. In relation to the enhancements and electrification of the Great Western Main Line, it is responsible for monitoring the delivery of certain regulated outputs set out in Network Rail’s Enhancements Delivery Plan.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-07-04T15:44:07.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732500/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732500/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732500/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-06-26","Great Western Railway Line: Electrification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the role of the Office of Rail and Road is in relation to the full electrification of the Great Western mainline to Bristol.","false","Biography information for Karin Smyth","Bristol South","Karin Smyth","1174"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732501","Department for Education","true","2017-07-05","<p>All schools must comply with strict building and fire safety regulations. It has always been the case that where a fire risk assessment required for any new building recommends sprinklers are installed to keep children safe, they must be fitted.</p><p>As not all new schools are commissioned by the Department for Education we do not hold data on the number of all new schools that have been built with or without sprinklers installed.</p><p>The Department holds information on schools managed centrally by the Education and Skills Funding Agency, under the Priority Schools Building Programme (PSBP). Of the 260 schools in phase one of the PSBP, 7<ins class="ministerial">4</ins><del class="ministerial">5</del> schools include sprinkler systems. As schools under phase two of the PSBP are still in the early design stage, it is not yet clear which may require sprinklers at this time.</p><p><ins class="ministerial">The number of schools in phase one with sprinklers installed had previously been reported as 75. However, further analysis of the data has confirmed that a joint project between two primary schools in Wiltshire had inadvertently been counted as two schools, when they should only have been counted once. Therefore, we can confirm that the correct number of schools fitted with sprinklers, under phase one of PSBP, is 74</ins></p><p>Until recently, schools developed under the Free Schools programme were managed by the individual Free School proposer groups, via their appointed building contractors. Due to this, the Department does not hold information on the number of Free School buildings with and without sprinklers installed.</p><p>All schools must have robust safety plans to follow in the event of a fire and have very strong safety features. This includes the fact that they are not occupied overnight and are generally low rise with multiple exit routes.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-07-05T16:20:35.423Z","2017-10-04T11:07:35.163Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732501/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732501/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732501/answer","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732501/answer/previousversion/2132","Biography information for Nick Gibb","60","Education","Education","2017-06-26","Schools: Fire Extinguishers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many new schools have been built (a) with and (b) without a sprinkler system fitted in each year since 2010-11.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","1093"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732502","Department for Education","false","2017-07-05","<p>All schools must comply with strict building and fire safety regulations. It has always been the case that where a fire risk assessment required for any new building recommends sprinklers are installed to keep children safe, they must be fitted.</p><p>As not all new schools are commissioned by the Department for Education we do not hold data on the number of all new schools that have been built with or without sprinklers installed.</p><p>The Department holds information on schools managed centrally by the Education and Skills Funding Agency, under the Priority Schools Building Programme (PSBP). Of the 260 schools in phase one of the PSBP, 75 schools include sprinkler systems. As schools under phase two of the PSBP are still in the early design stage, it is not yet clear which may require sprinklers at this time.</p><p> </p><p>Until recently, schools developed under the Free Schools programme were managed by the individual Free School proposer groups, via their appointed building contractors. Due to this, the Department does not hold information on the number of Free School buildings with and without sprinklers installed.</p><p>All schools must have robust safety plans to follow in the event of a fire and have very strong safety features. This includes the fact that they are not occupied overnight and are generally low rise with multiple exit routes.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","1093","2017-07-05T16:20:35.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732502/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732502/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732502/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-26","Free Schools: Fire Extinguishers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, which free schools do not have a sprinkler system.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","1175"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732503","HM Treasury","false","2017-06-29","<p>The future relationship between the UK and the EIB is something that will be determined as part of the negotiations on the UK’s exit from the EU and the Government will not be giving a running commentary on these negotiations.</p><p> </p><p>The EIB publishes details of all their projects on their website. Financing details of all projects, including those in Scotland, for each of the past 10 years can be found in the link below</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.eib.org/projects/loan/list/?region=1&amp;country=GB" target="_blank">http://www.eib.org/projects/loan/list/?region=1&amp;country=GB</a></p><p> </p><p>As part of the ongoing work on the UKs exit from the EU, HMT has been assessing the contribution EIB finance makes to the UK economy. In his Mansion House speech on 20 June, the Chancellor said that; “The European Investment Bank, and its offshoot, the European Investment Fund, have been an important source of funding for infrastructure investment and for growth businesses.”</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-06-29T07:35:38.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732503/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732503/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732503/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-06-26","European Investment Bank","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will take steps to ensure that Scotland remains eligible for, and retains access to, European Investment Bank funding after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","1041"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732504","HM Treasury","false","2017-06-29","<p>Kinship care is a form of foster care and where individuals are receiving allowances from local authorities in return for providing the care, they will be self-employed and will need to register with HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC). Qualifying care relief will be available in relation to the allowance paid by the local authority.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC has published guidance on Gov.uk to help kinship carers:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/qualifying-care-relief-foster-carers-adult-placement-carers-kinship-carers-and-staying-put-carers-hs236-self-assessment-helpsheet/hs236-qualifying-care-relief-foster-carers-adult-placement-carers-kinship-carers-and-staying-put-carers-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/qualifying-care-relief-foster-carers-adult-placement-carers-kinship-carers-and-staying-put-carers-hs236-self-assessment-helpsheet/hs236-qualifying-care-relief-foster-carers-adult-placement-carers-kinship-carers-and-staying-put-carers-2015</a></p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-06-29T13:45:47.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732504/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732504/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732504/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-06-26","Carers: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether kinship carers in Scotland who do not receive a fee for the role they perform and receive kinship care allowance from a local authority are required to register as self-employed.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","1221"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732505","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-06-29","<p>Any Government proposals on further UK restrictions on the sale of ivory would be subject to consultation. Only following such a consultation, where Government is able to gather views and evidence to evaluate the impact and likely effectiveness of any proposals, can a full evaluation be completed.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-06-29T15:28:03.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732505/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732505/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732505/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-06-26","Ivory: Sales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, with reference to the Answer of 18 April 2017 to Question 69979, for what reasons that Answer does not refer to any assessment of the effectiveness of the ban on the sale of antique ivory objects made after 1947.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","1236"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732506","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-06-29","<p>Defra publishes extensive air quality information on its UK Air website (uk-air.defra.gov.uk) as well as disseminating up-to-date information through social media, emails and Freephone services. Information on this website includes daily air pollution forecasts and hourly monitoring data from national monitoring sites, alongside associated health advice. The website also holds research reports and a back catalogue of historical monitoring and modelling data made available as open data.</p><p> </p><p>There is an effective cross-government system in place for giving health advice to the public during periods of high air pollution. Defra, Public Health England and the Met Office work closely together to issue up-to-date postcode-specific forecasts, bulletins and social media updates. We also work with health charities to make sure vulnerable people are aware of any periods of low air quality.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, local authorities monitor air pollution and make this information available locally.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-06-29T15:34:56.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732506/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732506/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732506/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-06-26","Air Pollution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what plans his Department has to promote public knowledge of air pollution levels across the UK.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","1237"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732507","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-04","<p>This Government remains committed to encouraging more people to engage in sport and physical activity, regardless of their background or level of ability.</p><p> </p><p>The Government's Sporting Future strategy published in December 2015 set out that, in future, public investment in sport and physical activity will be based on the contribution that organisations can make to five broad outcomes: Physical Wellbeing; Mental Wellbeing; Individual Development; Social and Community Development; and Economic Development. Cycling, including off-road cycling, is included as part of the strategy. Officials at DCMS are engaged with Defra officials as they develop their Environment Strategy.</p><p> </p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-07-04T09:58:22.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732507/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732507/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732507/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-06-26","Cycling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to the Answer of 20 March 2017 to Question 68586, what discussions has she had with her counterpart in the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs on opportunities to increase off-road cycling as part of that Department's Environment Strategy.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","1228"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732508","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-07-04","<p>There is a programme of work building on the recommendations from the Environmental Audit Committee’s inquiry into microbeads. Although there is no specific assessment of the impacts on freshwater wildlife planned at this time, this is an area of ongoing interest in the research community more widely. As with any area of emerging research on the natural environment, our scientists keep outputs under review and scan the horizon for emerging issues, including through working with external experts such as the Science Advisory Council and other committees.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-07-04T10:30:54.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732508/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732508/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732508/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-06-26","Microplastics: Animal Welfare","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, with reference to the Answer of 18 April 2017 to Question 69988, whether his Department plans to assess the effects of microplastics on the welfare of non-marine wildlife.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","1229"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732509","Department of Health","false","2017-07-04","<p>The United Kingdom Government, from an environmental perspective, is conducting research on the capacity for microplastics to cause harm in the marine environment and implications for the food chain. The most likely human exposure to microplastics from the marine environment is via the ingestion of seafood.</p><p> </p><p>The Food Standards Agency (FSA) has been monitoring the scientific evidence concerning the occurrence and effects of microplastics in seafood. On the basis of current information, the FSA considers it is unlikely that the presence of the low levels of microplastic particles that have been reported to occur in certain types of seafood would cause harm to consumers. The FSA will continue to monitor and assess emerging information concerning microplastics in food.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-07-04T11:18:49.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732509/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732509/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732509/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-06-26","Microplastics: Health Hazards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to the Answer of 18 April 2017 to Question 70013, for what reasons that Answer does not refer to the reasons why his Department is not planning to conduct an assessment of the implications of microplastics entering the marine environment on human health.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","1230"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732510","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-07-03","<p>The projected total savings as a result of the Strategic Defence and Security Review 2010 and work undertaken in 2011 to reduce the number of Regular Army personnel was £10.6 billion between 2011-12 and 2021-22.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-07-03T15:24:39.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732510/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732510/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732510/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-06-26","Army","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what total savings his Department has made as a result of reducing British Army personnel since the Strategic Defence and Security Review 2010.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","1231"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732511","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-05","<p>The UK has in place various arrangements to ensure the protection of classified information exchanged with international partners and organisations. Such arrangements are kept under regular review.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-07-05T16:22:09.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732511/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732511/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/732511/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-06-26","Intelligence Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what assessment his Department has made of the security of intelligence shared between signatories of the Five Eyes alliance.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","1232"
